## 0. TL;DR (read this, then Ã‚Â§4 and Ã‚Â§6)
- **Symptom:** close, soft-skinned characters (Jawas/robed NPCs) render with vertical "texture spikes" + detached floating boots in-world (Mos Eisley). D3D9 is clean. D3D11-only.
- **Breakthrough (Capture15, 2026-06-05):** the torn draws have **perfectly clean vertex data in the captured buffers** (RenderDoc re-runs their VS and gets correct geometry) but render torn **live**. Ã¢â€¡â€™ it is a **capture-invisible CPU-write / GPU-read RACE**. The vertex data is *correct*; the live GPU read it at the wrong moment.
- **Consequence:** the **5 buffer-data/lifetime fixes I tried all failed** because the VB data was never corrupt Ã¢â‚¬â€ you cannot fix a timing race by reshaping correct data.
- **Current staged build:** a **GPU-serialization diagnostic** is enabled in `Direct3d11_Device::present()` (full CPUÃ¢â€ â€GPU sync each frame). **Run it and report whether the spikes vanish** Ã¢â‚¬â€ that single result decides the fix direction (Ã‚Â§6).
- Everything else is reverted to baseline. An intermittent `nvwgf2um` (NVIDIA driver) crash on world load is **pre-existing and not ours** (Ã‚Â§8) Ã¢â‚¬â€ retry to clear.

---

## 1. Exact symptom
- Vertical brown "texture spikes" erupt from robed/garment characters; the robe texture is stretched along the spike. Some skinned sub-parts (e.g. **boots**) detach and float as **intact units** elsewhere in the scene.
- **Distance/LOD-dependent:** the SAME Jawa is clean at a distance and tears up close. Skinning mode is chosen by on-screen size in `SkeletalAppearance2.cpp:1737`:
  - far/tiny Ã¢â€ â€™ `SM_noSkinning`
  - medium Ã¢â€ â€™ `SM_hardSkinning`
  - **close/large Ã¢â€ â€™ `SM_softSkinning`**  Ã¢â€ Â the torn case (CPU-skinned into a dynamic VB every frame)
- **D3D11-only:** D3D9 (`gl05`, `rasterMajor=5`) renders the same character clean at all distances.
- **In-world-specific:** char-select soft-skinned bodies render CLEAN (same VS, same input layout, same `skinData`) Ã¢â‚¬â€ see `[[project_phase17_charselect_d3d11_parity_verified]]`. So the core skinning/VS/layout is fine; something about the busy in-world scene triggers it.
- Severity flickers frame-to-frame (mild Ã¢â€ â€™ extreme).

---

## 2. Architecture (file:line, verified this saga)
Soft-skin path Ã¢â‚¬â€ `clientSkeletalAnimation/src/shared/appearance/SoftwareBlendSkeletalShaderPrimitive.cpp`:
- `prepareToDraw()` @483. Multi-stream branch @566-581: `skinData()` writes positions+normals into `m_systemStream` (a SystemVertexBuffer), then `m_dynamicStream->lock(m_vertexCount)` + copy systemStreamÃ¢â€ â€™dynamic + `unlock()`. Non-multistream variants @586-619.
- The skinning fill `fillVertexBuffer()` @1617 writes ALL `m_vertexCount` verts (loops @1640 / @1690) Ã¢â‚¬â€ position, normal, texcoord per vertex.
- `RenderCommand::render()` @306-315 issues `(*m_drawPrimitiveCommand)(0, m_minimumVertexBufferIndex, m_numberOfVertices, m_startIndexBufferIndex, m_primitiveCount)` Ã¢â€ â€™ `Graphics::drawIndexedTriangleList(baseVertexIndex=0, minVbIndex, numVerts, startIndex, primCount)`. **baseVertex=0; IB holds ABSOLUTE indices.**
- Index buffer built in `buildIndexBufferAndRenderCommands()` @1291; **`m_indexBuffer = new StaticIndexBuffer(indexCount)` @1298 Ã¢â‚¬â€ a STATIC IB for the single-mesh path (NOT the dynamic ring).** `createTriList(minVbIndex, (maxVbIndex-minVbIndex)+1, firstTriListIndex, triCount)` @1369.
- `m_vertexCount = mesh.getVertexCount(...)` @1019; `m_staticStream`/`m_systemStream` sized `m_vertexCount` @1224/1231; `m_dynamicStream = new DynamicVertexBuffer(dynamicFormat)` @1106.

Batched path Ã¢â‚¬â€ `clientSkeletalAnimation/src/shared/batch/FullGeometrySkeletalAppearanceBatchRenderer.cpp` (batches multiple chars into ONE dynamic VB + ONE dynamic IB):
- `LocalShaderPrimitive::draw()` @298; do-while loop @317-352. `allowDiscard` decided @312-343: `getNumberOfLockableDynamicVertices(false)` @322; if a source mesh won't fit remaining Ã¢â€ â€™ `allowDiscard=true` @340 (a real mid-frame `forceDiscard`).
- `renderBuffers()` @178: `s_batchVertexBuffer->lock(vertexCount, allowDiscard)` @191; `s_batchIndexBuffer->lock(indexCount)` @195 (dynamic IB); copies verts + **adjusts indices `*destIbIt = *sourceIbIt + copiedVertexCount` @238**; then draws each chunk.

D3D11 dynamic buffers (the suspects):
- `Direct3d11_DynamicVertexBufferData.{h,cpp}` Ã¢â‚¬â€ ONE process-wide shared ring (`ms_d3dRingBuffer`, `D3D11_USAGE_DYNAMIC`, ~2MB), `lock()` Map(WRITE_DISCARD on wrap / WRITE_NO_OVERWRITE on append), over-charge accounting (`ms_used += length` in lock), `getSharedRingBuffer()`, `beginFrame()` @144 **has ZERO call sites**, `getNumberOfLockableDynamicVertices()`.
- `Direct3d11_DynamicIndexBufferData.cpp` Ã¢â‚¬â€ the **dynamic INDEX ring**, same shared-ring architecture, `getSharedRingBuffer()` @125, `beginFrame()` zero callers. **NEVER modified in any of the 5 fixes.** Used by the batcher (`s_batchIndexBuffer`). Single soft-skin meshes use a STATIC IB.
- Bind sites: single-stream VB `Direct3d11_StateCache.cpp:2265`; dynamic IB `Direct3d11_StateCache.cpp:2364`; multi-stream VB `Direct3d11_VertexBufferVectorData.cpp:143`. Draw: `drawPartialIndexedTriangleList()` @3223 Ã¢â€ â€™ `DrawIndexed(primCount*3, startIndex, baseIndex)` (D3D11 has **no** min/numVertices bound, unlike D3D9 `DrawIndexedPrimitive`).
- Once-per-frame hook: `Direct3d11.cpp` `update_impl()` @289 = `ms_glApi.update` @1011 = `Graphics::update`, fires every frame BEFORE the first `beginScene`. (`beginScene` is PER-PASS Ã¢â‚¬â€ resetting dynamic state there shreds geometry because draws defer across passes; proven catastrophic.)
- `Direct3d11_Device::present()` @847 Ã¢â‚¬â€ once per frame; the serialization diagnostic block lives here ~@868.

D3D9 reference: `Direct3d9_DynamicVertexBufferData.cpp` lock@172 (no ms_used advance) / unlock@244 (`ms_used += actual`); `Direct3d9.cpp:2484` calls `beginFrame()` inside `beginScene` (D3D9 wraps the whole frame in one BeginScene/EndScene).

