Confirmed: the only mechanism left that fits the gold-standard readback is an indexed fetch past the written dynamic-VB slice.

The key path is:

- [SoftwareBlendSkeletalShaderPrimitive.cpp](D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/library/clientSkeletalAnimation/src/shared/appearance/SoftwareBlendSkeletalShaderPrimitive.cpp:737) locks/writes exactly `m_vertexCount`.
- [SoftwareBlendSkeletalShaderPrimitive.cpp](D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/library/clientSkeletalAnimation/src/shared/appearance/SoftwareBlendSkeletalShaderPrimitive.cpp:1544) builds render commands from IB-derived `minVbIndex/maxVbIndex`.
- [RenderCommand::render](D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/library/clientSkeletalAnimation/src/shared/appearance/SoftwareBlendSkeletalShaderPrimitive.cpp:306) passes `baseIndex=0`, `minimumVertexIndex`, `numberOfVertices`, `startIndex`, `primitiveCount`.
- [D3D11 drawPartialIndexedTriangleList](D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/application/Direct3d11/src/win32/Direct3d11_StateCache.cpp:3221) ignores the range for actual draw and issues `DrawIndexed(..., startIndex, baseIndex)`.
- [D3D9](D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/application/Direct3d9/src/win32/Direct3d9.cpp:4157) passes that range to `DrawIndexedPrimitive(..., minimumVertexIndex, numberOfVertices, ...)`.

So if your probe logs `minimumVertexIndex + numberOfVertices - 1 >= runStart`, that is effectively proof. Those values are computed from the same copied IB values in [buildIndexBufferAndRenderCommands](D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/library/clientSkeletalAnimation/src/shared/appearance/SoftwareBlendSkeletalShaderPrimitive.cpp:1518), not invented by D3D11.

Where the mismatch likely comes from: per-shader used-vertex compaction. `m_vertexCount` is `MeshConstructionHelper::getVertexCount()`, which returns `m_usedVertexCount` ([MeshConstructionHelper.cpp](D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/library/clientSkeletalAnimation/src/shared/appearance/MeshConstructionHelper.cpp:1234)). Tri lists are supposed to remap original shader indices through `m_shaderVertexIndex` ([MeshConstructionHelper.cpp](D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/library/clientSkeletalAnimation/src/shared/appearance/MeshConstructionHelper.cpp:1468)). If a tri-list IB still exceeds `m_usedVertexCount`, that remap invariant failed or stale/corrupt mesh data entered the static IB. Tri strips are more suspicious by code, because `getTriStripVertexIndex()` returns the stored index directly ([MeshConstructionHelper.cpp](D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/library/clientSkeletalAnimation/src/shared/appearance/MeshConstructionHelper.cpp:1426)), but your cited draw path is triangle-list, so scan the actual static IB for the sampled draw before blaming strips.

Minimal fix: fix/validate the index data at build, not the D3D11 ring.

Do not lock `maxIndexUsed + 1`; there is no valid source/skinned vertex data beyond `m_vertexCount`, so that just pads undefined references. Do not zero-pad as a fix; it still draws triangles to origin. Clamping is only acceptable as a diagnostic or last-ditch skip policy.

Best minimal code fix is in `buildIndexBufferAndRenderCommands`: compute `vertexCount = mesh.getVertexCount(meshPerShaderData)` before copying indices, and for each generated index validate `0 <= index < vertexCount`. For release behavior, skip any triangle containing an invalid index and log once per asset/shader; for debug, `DEBUG_FATAL` so the bad mesh/remap path is exposed. Then create render commands from the surviving valid indices. The true fix is to correct the mesh/remap producer so generated IBs are always in `[0, m_vertexCount)`.

If indices are actually bounded, then this draw cannot be the source of the visible spike. In that case the remaining explanations are: you sampled a nearby garment draw but not the spike-owning draw, or an in-range but wrong IB connects valid vertices badly. A transform/constant issue would move the whole primitive, not collapse only the out-of-range subset to exact zero; the dynamic IB path does not apply to this single soft-skin primitive because it uses a static IB.

Discard inversion: the read-past is constant; discard policy only changes what lives after the valid slice. Fresh D3D11 discard generations often expose zero tail, so invalid indices collapse to origin. Reduced discard/reuse leaves stale geometry in the tail, so the same invalid indices fetch nonzero garbage and flicker worse.
